article.description: Tangela Smith and Yolanda Griffith each scored 17 points Friday to lead Sacramento to a 65-59 victory over Houston in the opening game of their best-of-three WNBA playoff series.
article.headline: Monarchs withstand Swoopes' 27 points
article.linkText: Houston, we have a problem: Monarchs take 1-0 lead
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- It's been a long time since the
Houston Comets ruled the WNBA.

Tangela Smith and Yolanda Griffith each scored 17 points Friday
night to lead the Sacramento Monarchs to a 65-59 victory over the
Comets in the opening game of their best-of-three WNBA playoff
series.

"I don't think I'm going home and make a thousand changes,"
Houston coach Van Chancellor said. "I just told our players we
have to win one game. You can't worry about winning two right
now."

Sacramento saw a 15-point lead shrink to 60-59 when Janeth
Arcain scored on a driving layup with 23 seconds left. Arcain
finished with 13 points.

But Kara Lawson made a free throw and Griffith and Smith
combined for four more in the final 10 seconds to give Sacramento
the win.

"I'm really glad we held on to win this one, it would have been
really tough to go down there and win two straight," Monarchs
coach John Whisenant said.

Game 2 is Sunday in Houston.

Sheryl Swoopes had 27 points and nine rebounds for the Comets.
She led a second rally for Houston, which scored 11 straight points
to pull within 48-44 with 5:37 remaining.

It was the fourth straight loss for Houston, which before losing
three in a row to end the regular season, had never lost more than
two straight games.

Lawson had 12 points and DeMya Walker added eight for
Sacramento. Smith had 10 rebounds.

The Comets had serious offensive problems and Swoopes scored
their first 15 points. It wasn't until Ukari Figgs made a 3-pointer
with 4:38 in the first half that another Houston player scored.

"Swoopes had 15 points at the half, Figgs had six and everyone
else went blank," Chancellor said. "You can't do that against a
good team."

The Monarchs, who went 14-for-27 from the field in taking a
32-21 halftime lead.

It was a struggle most of game for Tina Thompson, Houston's
leading scorer during the regular season. Thompson, who scored
seven points, missed her first seven shots and didn't have a point
until finally connecting from the perimeter with 13:02 to play.

"Defense has been our bread and butter the second half of the
season," Smith said. "We believe in it. We play aggressive as we
can. I think that was a big difference tonight, we wanted it a
little more."
